“He who has a why to live for can bear almost any how” is a quote attributed to Viktor Frankl, who survived the Holocaust. Frankl believed that having a sense of purpose is essential for enduring hardship.   Viktor E. Frankl (1905-1997) is best known for his profoundly inspiring book, Man's Search for Meaning. In the epic book, which has sold more than 10 million copies in at least 24 different languages, Frankl, a psychotherapist, describes poignantly his experience at the infamous Auschwitz concentration camps during the Holocaust.  He observed that those prisoners who gave up on life, who had lost all hope for a future, were inevitably the first to die.

To survive the Holocaust, Frankl would keep hope (and himself) alive by summoning up thoughts of his wife and the prospect of seeing her again, and by dreaming at one point lecturing after the war about the psychological lessons to be learned from his Auschwitz experience.

What about us?  What is the “Why” or purpose of your life?  For us who are Christians, the purpose of life is to glorify God, live a holy life, and share the Gospel with others.  What steps have you taken to know this Why more deeply?
